04779nam a22007455i 9780691186191DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911861917 a10.1515/97806911861912doi  a(DE-B1597)501861  a(OCoLC)1076473116  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBV2625b.K53 2009eb 7aHIS0360002bisacsh 7aSOC0310002bisacsh 7aSOC0480002bisacsh04a261.2/709732221 aKidd, Thomas S., eauthor.10aAmerican Christians and Islam :bEvangelical Culture and Muslims from the Colonial Period to the Age of Terrorism /cThomas S. Kidd. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList Of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1: Early American Christians and Islam -- tChapter 2: The Barbary Wars, the Last Days, and Islam in Early National America -- tChapter 3: Foreign Missions to Muslims in Nineteenth-Century America -- tChapter 4: Samuel Zwemer,World War I, and "The Evangelization of the Moslem World in This Generation" -- tChapter 5: The New Missionary Overture to Muslims and the Arab-Israeli Crisis -- tChapter 6: Christians Respond to Muslims in Modern America -- tChapter 7: Maturing Evangelical Missions and War in the Middle East -- tChapter 8: American Christians and Islam After September 11, 2001 -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex  aIn the wake of the September 11 terrorist attacks, many of America's Christian evangelicals have denounced Islam as a "demonic" and inherently violent religion, provoking frustration among other Christian conservatives who wish to present a more appealing message to the world's Muslims. Yet as Thomas Kidd reveals in this sobering book, the conflicted views expressed by today's evangelicals have deep roots in American history. Tracing Islam's role in the popular imagination of American Christians from the colonial period to today, Kidd demonstrates that Protestant evangelicals have viewed Islam as a global threat--while also actively seeking to convert Muslims to the Christian faith--since the nation's founding. He shows how accounts of "Mahometan" despotism and lurid stories of European enslavement by Barbary pirates fueled early evangelicals' fears concerning Islam, and describes the growing conservatism of American missions to Muslim lands up through the post-World War II era. Kidd exposes American Christians' anxieties about an internal Islamic threat from groups like the Nation of Islam in the 1960s and America's immigrant Muslim population today, and he demonstrates why Islam has become central to evangelical "end-times" narratives. Pointing to many evangelicals' unwillingness to acknowledge Islam's theological commonalities with Christianity and their continued portrayal of Islam as an "evil" and false religion, Kidd explains why Christians themselves are ironically to blame for the failure of evangelism in the Muslim world. American Christians and Islam is essential reading for anyone seeking to understand the causes of the mounting tensions between Christians and Muslims today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aIslamxPublic opinionxHistory. 0aMissions to MuslimsxHistory. 0aMissions, AmericanxHistory. 0aPublic opinionzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691186191zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691186191.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  a